Basics of statistical analysis in R for neurochemists

KN7001 neurochemistry with molecular neurobiology

R is an free open-source programming language, used often for data science, statistical analysis of small or large datasets and for data visualisation.

R is free to use

R is very versatile and can be used for anything from basic ploting of a few data points, to advanced analysis of transcriptomic and genomic data. In this tutorial we will demonstrate basic usage of R for data analysis, statistics and visualisation.

The power of R lies in many packages (or libraries) that are written by the community and make our lives easier when we analyze or visualize data. In addition there is active community and many forums posts dealing with error messages exist. It’s also easy to ask on forums about a specific problem.

Interface

Analysis in R is typically done in an IDE (Integrated Desktop Environment) - the most common for R is called RStudio https://posit.co/products/open-source/rstudio/


Prerequirement: Have installed R and Rstudio on your computer


Example 1: Statistical analysis of neurite outgrowth

In this experiment we performed measurements of neurite outgrowth upon 2 different treatments with differentiation factors and one control in cell culture. Neurite outgrowth was measured using automated analysis pipeline and results were exported in a csv file.

We will perform data import, basic QC, visualization and statistical testing of significance.

The tutorial has instructions shown as regular text and code shown in a grey box. You can copy-paste the code from the grey box into your RStudio session. Some code blocks might require minor edits to work for you.

Task 1: Import the csv file into R

In order to analyze the data it needs first to be imported and stored in computer memory (RAM). Then we can manipulate, reformat, clean, visualize the data and perform statistical analysis.

Data import from csv file is done typically using “read.csv” function. We will store the contents of the file in a object called neurites.

“<-” operator assignes the output of the function “read.csv” with parameter specifying file name to a variable “neurites”



First download the data from the github repository at link

Then run the following:

2. Data visualization


We can easily visualize the mean of samples on barplot

# First calculate means for all 3 conditions
mean1 <- mean(neurites$control)
mean2 <- mean(neurites$condition_1)
mean3 <- mean(neurites$condition_2)

# Then plot the means using a barplot
barplot(c(mean1,mean2,mean3),names.arg = c('control','condition_1','condition_2'))

# Note: In this command we concatenate the 3 means using function c() with 3 arguments
# Compare the following 2 commands:
# 1,2,3
# 'a','b','c'

c(1,2,3)
## [1] 1 2 3
c('a','b','c')
## [1] "a" "b" "c"
# We can also plot each single observation (on the y-axis) against the index of the observation (Y-axis) 

plot(unlist(neurites))

# Note: This only works because the data is sorted in columns, if it would not be sorted/grouped the points would have random inedexes and plot would be a mess

Any plot can be saved into a pdf file 

# First open a pdf file
pdf(file = 'Neurites_plot.pdf',width=3, height=6)

# Plot into the open file
barplot(c(mean1,mean2,mean3),names.arg = c('control','condition_1','condition_2'))

For analysis and visualisation we sometimes want to convert the data from wide to long format. This is especially useful for independent measurements.

Wide format can be useful for example if we have multiple timepoints of measurement, or multiple genes measured per sample. In our case the measurements are in different samples and are independent.

# Let's convert the neurites dataset into wide format: 
library(reshape2)
neurites.long <- melt(neurites)
## No id variables; using all as measure variables
head(neurites.long)
View(neurites.long)

We now have the data organised in one column with variables (control/condition_1/condition_2) and one column with values. This data format is called long format and can be useful for some types of analysis and visualisations.

# We can ask when does is the variable control ? -> Returns a vector with TRUE/FALSE 
neurites.long$variable == 'control'
##  [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
## [13]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [25] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [37] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [49] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
# We can now use this vector to only recover the part of data frame with control observations as follows: 
neurites.long[neurites.long$variable=='control',]
neurites.long[neurites.long$variable=='condition_1',]

More advanced way how to visualize the data using ggplot2 package

ggplot is a standard package used to visualize data in R. It provides much nicer aesthetics and more customisation than the base R functions like plot, barplot or boxplot. Let’s reproduce some of our previous plots in ggplot.

ggplot works in layers and layers are stacked on top of each other using + sign

library(ggplot2)
library(ggridges)
library(ggthemes)

# ggplot always uses long format for plotting
ggplot(data = neurites.long) + geom_bar(aes(x=variable,y=value), stat='summary',fun.y='mean')
## Warning in geom_bar(aes(x = variable, y = value), stat = "summary", fun.y =
## "mean"): Ignoring unknown parameters: `fun.y`
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`

# ggplot(data=) == initializes a ggplot object
# geom_bar adds a layer with barplot
# stat=summary tells it to use summary statistics and fun.y tells it to use mean as functon to calculate summary statistics
# aes() contains information about what should be on x and y axes

# Let's add some color to the plot
ggplot(data = neurites.long) + geom_bar(aes(x=variable,y=value,fill=variable), stat='summary',fun.y='mean',col='black')
## Warning in geom_bar(aes(x = variable, y = value, fill = variable), stat =
## "summary", : Ignoring unknown parameters: `fun.y`
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`

# We can also easily change the theme of the plot by adding theme layer - theme_base() makes it look more like a base R plot
ggplot(data = neurites.long) + geom_bar(aes(x=variable,y=value,fill=variable), stat='summary',fun.y='mean',col='black') + theme_base()
## Warning in geom_bar(aes(x = variable, y = value, fill = variable), stat =
## "summary", : Ignoring unknown parameters: `fun.y`
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`

# Let's plot histogram in ggplot - this histogram ignores the information about the variable. It just pools our control, and conditions into a single graph
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_histogram(aes(x=value))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# To split the histograms into 3 different ones, we can use facet_wrap layer to split the plots
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_histogram(aes(x=value)) + facet_wrap(~variable) 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# Let's add some color again
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_histogram(aes(x=value,fill=variable),col='black') + facet_wrap(~variable) # Creates 3 histograms for our 3 variables
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# And change the theme
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_histogram(aes(x=value,fill=variable),col='black') + facet_wrap(~variable) + theme_classic()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Let’s create a boxplot in ggplot

# Basic boxplot
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_boxplot(aes(x=variable,y=value))

# Add some color
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_boxplot(aes(x=variable,y=value,fill=variable))

# Because of layer based syntax we can stack layers on top of each other
# Let's add individual datapoints to the boxplot
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_boxplot(aes(x=variable,y=value,fill=variable)) + geom_point(aes(x=variable,y=value))

# The points are all in one row, we can add some jitter to avoid overplotting 
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_boxplot(aes(x=variable,y=value,fill=variable)) + geom_jitter(aes(x=variable,y=value),width = 0.25)

# If we skip the boxplot, we can just have a jitter plot
ggplot(data=neurites.long) +  geom_jitter(aes(x=variable,y=value),width = 0.25)

# And with some colors
ggplot(data=neurites.long) +  geom_jitter(aes(x=variable,y=value,col=variable),width = 0.25)

# Let's now fix  some axis labels
ggplot(data=neurites.long) +  geom_jitter(aes(x=variable,y=value,col=variable),width = 0.25) + xlab("condition") + ylab("Neurite length [um]")

# Density ridge histogram
ggplot(data=neurites.long) + geom_density_ridges(aes(x=value,y=variable,fill=variable)) + theme_bw()
## Picking joint bandwidth of 0.579

# Violin plot
ggplot(data = neurites.long) + geom_violin(aes(y=value,x=variable,fill=variable)) + theme_bw()

# With dots
ggplot(data = neurites.long) + geom_violin(aes(y=value,x=variable,fill=variable)) + geom_jitter(aes(x=variable,y=value),width=0.15) + theme_bw()

Task 3: Which statistical test should I use to compare the groups ?

Is my data normally distributed ?

Many statistical tests, especially parametric tests like the t-test, ANOVA, and linear regression, assume that the data follows a normal distribution. These tests rely on the properties of the normal distribution to calculate probabilities and critical values

1. Visual inspection

We can plot histogram of the data using function hist()

neurites
hist(neurites$control)

hist(neurites$condition_1)

hist(neurites$condition_2,breaks=5)

Exercise 3 : Function histogram() uses parameter ‘breaks=’ to specify the numbers of bins to plot. Experiment with changing this parameter and see if you can get nicer looking histogram






QQ plot

Q-Q plots (quantile-quantile plots) are useful way how to estimate normality of a data

The data is first fitted with normal distribution, and then compared to observed data.

If the data is normally distributed all the data points should be exactly on the fitted line

For more details on qqplot see here: link

library(ggpubr)
ggqqplot(neurites$control,title = 'QQ control')

ggqqplot(neurites$condition_1,title = 'QQ condition_1')

ggqqplot(neurites$condition_2,title = 'QQ condition_2')

### Numerical methods

If the data is normaly distributed median and mean of the measurements should be vey close to each other

Shapiro test of normality

There are several methods for normality test such as Kolmogorov-Smirnov (K-S) normality test and Shapiro-Wilk’s test.

Shapiro-Wilk’s method is widely recommended for normality test and it provides better power than K-S. It is based on the correlation between the data and the corresponding normal scores.

For more details on shapiro test see here link

shapiro.test(neurites$control)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  neurites$control
## W = 0.97049, p-value = 0.7652
shapiro.test(neurites$condition_1)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  neurites$condition_1
## W = 0.9803, p-value = 0.9379
shapiro.test(neurites$condition_2)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  neurites$condition_2
## W = 0.92259, p-value = 0.1111

Example of not normally distributed data

If we merge several normal distributions we typically don’t get normally distributed data. We can look at such example by mixing the data from our 3 conditions together

# Merge the data from all columns into single vector
mixed.data <- unname(unlist(neurites))
head(mixed.data)
## [1] 0.06372999 0.10308265 0.99902660 0.60876101 0.63159041 0.39914599
# QQ-plot and shapiro test for all data merged together
ggqqplot(mixed.data)

shapiro.test(mixed.data)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  mixed.data
## W = 0.64966, p-value = 1.066e-10

F test to compare sample variance

Comparing two variances is useful in several cases, including:

  • When you want to perform a two samples t-test to check the equality of the variances of the two samples
  • When you want to compare the variability of a new measurement method to an old one. Does the new method reduce the variability of the measure?
# To check the equality of variance between our conditions in a pairwise manner do the following: 
var.test(neurites$control,neurites$condition_1)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  neurites$control and neurites$condition_1
## F = 1.4325, num df = 19, denom df = 19, p-value = 0.4406
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5670153 3.6192325
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           1.432536
var.test(neurites$control,neurites$condition_2)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  neurites$control and neurites$condition_2
## F = 0.007197, num df = 19, denom df = 19, p-value = 3.68e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.002848664 0.018182894
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##         0.00719701
var.test(neurites$condition_1,neurites$condition_2)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  neurites$condition_1 and neurites$condition_2

Perform single t.test of 2 conditions

We use function t.test(). Use parameter var.equal to set if there is equal variance between the two samples

T.test with unequal variance is also called Welch t-test

test_1vs2 <- t.test(neurites$control, neurites$condition_1,var.equal = TRUE)
test_1vs2
